ans-serif;font-size:10pt;">Namaste Sir,<br> <br>People may misundersta=
nd the word "mokShayiShyAmi" (I shall liberate) in that verse based on what=
 their conditioning tells them liberation is. To get a correct understandin=
g, one may need to combine knowledge from other scriptures.<br> <br>As=
 an example, if the body of one having an attachment to the body is afflict=
ed with cancer, one may see it as a problem. Because one feels attachment a=
nd responsibility towards the body, one may be thinking about how to fix it=
 and may get agitated. So, one is not free from the negative repercussions =
of that cancer. But, when Ramana Maharshi or Ramakrishna Paramahamsa had ca=
ncer, they did not view it as a problem and displayed the same attitude
 an=
d mental equanimity. So, while their *bodies* experienced the repercussions=
 of that cancer, "they" were free from them.<br> <br>If one has surren=
dered one's sense of duty/responsibility towards *everything* as Lord says =
in that verse ("sarva dharmAn parityajya"), where "everything" inlcudes bod=
y, name, wife, children, properties etc, then anything bad (or good) happen=
ing to those entities will not touch one or bind one. One is "free" from th=
ose happenings. *That* liberation is what Lord says he shall give and the p=
re-condition is to give up any sense of duty/responsibility towards anythin=
g.<br> <br>*        *  &n=
bsp;     *<br> <br>Though some people interpret "d=
harma" in this verse as a religious path, the real meaning of dharma is "du=
ty, that which is correct". We have a sense of responsibility towards so ma=
ny entities, stemming from our conditioning (vasana). This
 includes a sens=
e of responsibility towards body, name, wife, children, parents, relatives,=
 community, country, religion, subjects of study (e.g. Jyotish) etc etc. Ev=
ery sense of "I need to do this", whether noble or evil, comes from one's c=
onditioning and *binds* one. If one surrenders all these, i.e. effectively =
one surrenders one's entire conditioning, at Lord's feet and accepts whatev=
er happens to one as god's prasad, then one is liberated.<br> <br>Base=
d on the "momentum" from actions before liberation, one may face various li=
fe situations even after liberation. In one case, one may get cancer and di=
e. In another case, one may roam the world and spread Sanatana Dharma. In a=
nother case, one may sit in a cave and meditate for 10,000 more years. In a=
nother case, one may roam the streets looking like a mad person. In another=
 case, one may continue to work as a day labourer. In another case, one may=
 destroy a kingdom in a battle. And so on. In all
 these cases, the liberat=
ed being has surrendered all preferences, all likes and dislikes, all agend=
as, attachments and sense of resposibility towards everything one has (body=
, name, wife, children etc and all attributes of the body-mind complex that=
 once ruled the roost) and engages in spontaneous actions based on the circ=
umstances one finds oneself in, based on pre-existing momentum. Nothing tha=
t happens to one binds one and nothing that one does binds one.<br> <b=
r>Liberation does not mean that all of one's belongings (body, name, family=
, community etc) are "safe" and "well". Nor does it mean that one does noth=
ing. Things may keep happening to one and one may keep doing things. Yet, o=
ne is untouched by them, like a water drop on a lotus leaf, because one has=
 no desires, demands, preferences or agendas and accepts whatever Lord give=
s.<br> <br>*        *  &n=
bsp;    
 *<br> <br>One who tells Krishna, "I surr=
ender to you. I will not follow any religion or rituals or gods and just pr=
ay to you. So forgive all my sins and make sure that only good things befal=
l my body, my name, my family etc [because I really care about them and any=
 damage to them will upset me]" has missed the point big time! The sublime =
verse you referred to is like the culmination of entire Bhagavad Gita and i=
s the essence of all Upanishads.<br> <br>*    &nbs=
p;   *        *<br> <br>O=
ne word of caution. IMHO, what follows is far more relevant to most readers=
 of this writeup than what lies above!<br> <br>This verse is the essen=
ce of Self-knowledge. But most people of this era are unlikely to realize S=
elf (until the end of this yuga cycle). So my suggestion is to set more rea=
sonable goals. It is ok if you haven't surrendered all of your dharmas to
 =
Lord.<br> <br>!!!!! In fact, even if you try, you will probably end up=
 misusing that notion to run away from most of your higher (and selfless) d=
harmas and yet end up sticking to your lowest and most selfish dharmas (e.g=
. dharma towards body and its survival instinct, very tough to shake off). =
That is useless. !!!!! <br> <br>No wonder Vedanta comes at the end of =
all Veda and the verse above comes after so many chapters on so many other =
things. Don't jump to it right away!<br> <br>First *expand* your sense=
 of self and your sense of responsibility and attachment to be more inclusi=
ve. Current body-mind complex we inhabit is a very limited notion of self. =
Expand it to family, then to community, then to town, then to nation etc. O=
r may be to a large community of people with certain attributes. Basically,=
 try to put others before you, learn to sacrifice and engage in more selfle=
ss actions than selfish actions. Not everyone may be liberated in
